/**
 * @mainpage AnalysisG Framework Documentation
 *
 * @section intro Introduction
 *
 * AnalysisG is a comprehensive Graph Neural Network Analysis Framework for
 * High Energy Physics (HEP). It provides a complete pipeline from raw physics
 * events to trained neural network models.
 *
 * @section architecture Framework Architecture
 *
 * The framework is organized into the following major components:
 *
 * @subsection primary_components Primary Components
 * 
 * - @ref events_module "Events Module" - Event processing and particle physics data structures
 * - @ref graphs_module "Graphs Module" - Graph construction from physics events  
 * - @ref models_module "Models Module" - Neural network model implementations
 * - @ref metrics_module "Metrics Module" - Performance evaluation and metrics
 *
 * @subsection infrastructure_components Infrastructure Components
 *
 * - @ref modules_infrastructure "Modules Infrastructure" - Core framework components:
 *   - @ref modules_particle "Particle" - Particle template and kinematics
 *   - @ref modules_event "Event" - Event template and processing
 *   - @ref modules_graph "Graph" - Graph template and data structures
 *   - @ref modules_model "Model" - Model template and training
 *   - @ref modules_metric "Metric" - Metric template and evaluation
 *   - @ref modules_io "I/O" - ROOT file reading/writing
 *   - @ref modules_dataloader "Dataloader" - Data loading and batching
 *   - @ref modules_optimizer "Optimizer" - Training optimization
 *   - @ref modules_structs "Structs" - Core data structures
 *   - @ref modules_tools "Tools" - Utility functions
 *   - @ref modules_nusol "NuSol" - Neutrino reconstruction
 *   - And 13 more submodules...
 *
 * - @ref pyc_module "Python-C++ Interface" - Python bindings via Cython:
 *   - @ref pyc_interface "Interface" - Main Python interface
 *   - @ref pyc_graph "Graph" - Graph Python bindings
 *   - @ref pyc_operators "Operators" - Tensor operations
 *   - @ref pyc_physics "Physics" - Physics calculations
 *   - @ref pyc_transform "Transform" - Data transformations
 *   - @ref pyc_nusol "NuSol" - Neutrino solver bindings
 *   - @ref pyc_cutils "C Utils" - Utility functions
 *
 * - @ref templates_module "Templates" - Code templates for extending the framework
 *
 * @section workflow Typical Workflow
 *
 * 1. **Event Processing**: Load physics events using event templates
 * 2. **Graph Construction**: Convert events to graphs using graph templates  
 * 3. **Model Training**: Train models using the model templates and infrastructure
 * 4. **Evaluation**: Evaluate performance using metrics
 *
 * @section getting_started Getting Started
 *
 * @subsection step1 Step 1: Understanding Events
 * Start with the @ref events_module to understand how physics events are represented.
 * Key classes: bsm_4tops, exp_mc20, gnn_event, ssml_mc20
 *
 * @subsection step2 Step 2: Graph Construction  
 * See @ref graphs_module for converting events to graphs.
 * Key classes: graph_bsm_4tops, graph_exp_mc20, graph_ssml_mc20
 *
 * @subsection step3 Step 3: Models
 * Explore @ref models_module for neural network architectures.
 * Key classes: grift, RecursiveGraphNeuralNetwork
 *
 * @subsection step4 Step 4: Training
 * Use @ref modules_infrastructure for the complete training pipeline.
 *
 * @section file_organization File Organization
 *
 * The framework follows a consistent structure:
 * ```
 * src/AnalysisG/
 * ├── events/       - Event implementations
 * ├── graphs/       - Graph implementations
 * ├── models/       - Model implementations
 * ├── metrics/      - Metric implementations
 * ├── modules/      - Infrastructure (24 submodules)
 * ├── pyc/          - Python bindings (7 submodules)
 * └── templates/    - Code templates
 * ```
 *
 * Each module typically contains:
 * - `cxx/` - Implementation files (.cxx)
 * - `include/` - Header files (.h)
 */
